# Doc scoring pre-commit hook

## About this directory

`.githooks` is a **fallback for contributors who do not have Node.js installed**
and therefore cannot use Husky, which is the primary pre-commit setup for this
repo (see `.husky/`).

Activating `.githooks` by setting `core.hooksPath` will disable Husky. Only do
this if you cannot use Husky. If you have Node installed, use Husky instead.

The two setups share the same base checks (`.husky/pre-commit-base.sh`) and the
same AI doc reviewer script (`.githooks/doc-review.sh`). The only difference is
that Husky also runs date metadata injection and lint-staged, which requires Node.

## Overview

The AI doc reviewer in this directory uses the unified style guide (derived from
the engineering style guide) to assess whether a doc is ready for a review from
a member of the education team.

The scoring reflects the overall content, style guide rules, and basic SEO.

## Scoring

The minimum score to complete the commit and push to the `web-unified-docs`
repository is configured per path. If the document does not meet the minimum
score, the check outputs a list of necessary fixes for the docs.

If you are having trouble getting your doc above the minimum score, contact your
technical writer for assistance.

## Prerequisites 

There are several preqs required to set up the script.

- GitHub account is a member of the HashiCorp GitHub organization
- GitHub account has access to Copilot
- OpenCode CLI installed
- OpenCode CLI authenticated to your HashiCorp GitHub account

## Set up prerequisites

1. Install the OpenCode CLI
   
   ```shell-session
   $ brew install anomalyco/tap/opencode
   ```

1. Add your IBM Copilot account.

   ```shell-session
   $ opencode auth login
   ```

1. Select `GitHub Copilot`.

1. Select `GitHub.com`.

1. Follow the prompts to complete the authentication. 

   If you have more than one GitHub account, select the account that belongs to
   the HashiCorp GitHub organization.

1. When prompted, click **Authorize anomalyco**.

   OpenCode CLI is now authenticated to HashiCorp GitHub Copilot.
   
   ```plaintext
   opencode auth login
   
   ┌  Add credential
   │
   ◇  Select provider
   │  GitHub Copilot
   │
   ◇  Select GitHub deployment type
   │  GitHub.com
   │
   ●  Go to: https://github.com/login/device
   │
   ●  Enter code: A2C4-E6G8
   │
   ◇  Login successful
   │
   └  Done
   ```

1. Verify the available models in the OpenCode CLI.

   ```shell-session
   $ opencode models
   opencode/big-pickle
   opencode/hy3-preview-free
   opencode/minimax-m2.5-free
   opencode/nemotron-3-super-free
   github-copilot/claude-opus-4.6
   github-copilot/claude-opus-4.7
   github-copilot/claude-sonnet-4.6
   github-copilot/gemini-2.5-pro
   github-copilot/gemini-3-flash-preview
   github-copilot/gemini-3.1-pro-preview
   ```

   The pre-commit script uses `github-copilot/claude-sonnet-4.6`.

1. Enable the AI doc reviewer. This works the same way whether you are using
   Husky or the `.githooks` fallback — the opt-in is a local git config flag.

   ```shell-session
   $ git config --local doc-review.enabled true
   ```

   **If you do not have Node.js installed** (cannot use Husky), you also need to
   activate the `.githooks` fallback path. **Skip this step if you have Node**.

   ```shell-session
   $ git config core.hooksPath .githooks
   ```

1. To disable the AI doc reviewer without changing your hook setup:

   ```shell-session
   $ git config --local doc-review.enabled false
   ```

1. To return to Husky (switches the hook path back to Husky):

   ```shell-session
   $ git config core.hooksPath .husky/_
   ```

OpenCode will scan any `.md` or `.mdx` file added to a directory configured in `doc-review.sh`
when you run `git commit`.